Clubfoot is a deformity in which an infant's foot is turned inward, often so severely that the bottom of the foot faces sideways or even upward. Approximately one infant in every 1,000 live births will have clubfoot, making it one of the more common congenital (present at birth) foot deformities. This however can be corrected through surgery! @cbmkenya in partnership with @curekenya and Safaricom Foundation have made it possible for kids who have orthopedic related issues to have a normal life through a program dubbed #WezeshaElimu where they undergo corrective surgery and are placed back to School.

As a photographer documenting a surgery can be quite a challenge especially if it involves blood. Thank God for cataract surgery there's no blood involved. I have documented cataract surgeries and the best thing about it, the patient goes in partially blind and comes out full of vision.

In cataract surgery, the lens inside your eye that has become cloudy is removed and replaced with an artificial lens (called an intraocular lens, or IOL) to restore clear vision. The procedure typically is performed on an outpatient basis and does not require an overnight stay in a hospital or other care facility.
